{"title_page": "Judge in charge of the Constitutional and Administrative Law List (Hong Kong)", "text_new": "{{short description|Hong Kong judges}}\nThe '''Judge in charge of the Constitutional and Administrative Law List''' of the [[Court of First Instance (Hong Kong)|Court of First Instance]] (within the [[High Court (Hong Kong)|High Court]]) of Hong Kong, is the most important Law List in that court, given the far-reaching powers of interpreting the [[Hong Kong Basic Law]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://heinonline.org/HOL/LandingPage?handle=hein.journals/judire8&div=22&id=&page=|title=Introduction to Judicial Review in Hong Kong|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> As such, the Judge in charge of this list is often considered to be the top judge of the lower court.\n\n==Description==\n\nThe list receives a material public interest in Hong Kong due to the fact that it is the first point of contact for most contentious court cases around issues that have caused public discussion or social unrest. These include cases around the [[Hong Kong Legislative Council oath-taking controversy|Legislative Council oath-taking controversy]], the [[Umbrella Movement]], and the [[2019\u201320 Hong Kong protests]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/law-and-crime/article/3033406/rare-significant-move-hong-kong-judiciary-appoints-two|title=In rare, \u2018significant\u2019 move, Hong Kong judiciary appoints two judges to hear legal challenges against anti-mask law|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In addition, given the important nature of this position, the Judge entrusted with this role is often almost guaranteed to be elevated to the higher courts in the future.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/2048895/high-court-judge-oath-taking-case-no-stranger-thorny|title=High Court judge in oath-taking case no stranger to thorny political issues|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> So far, all Judges in this role have been promoted to at least the Court of Appeal.\n\n== List of Judges==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!#\n!Name\n!Tenure\n!Promoted To (Most Senior Role) \n!Silk \n|-\n|1\n|[[Brian Keith (judge)|Sir Brian Richard Keith]]\n|1997\u201399\n|[[High Court of Hong Kong|Justice of Appeal of the High Court of Hong Kong]]\n|<small>[[Queen's Counsel|QC]] (1989)</small>\n|-\n|2\n|[[Frank Stock]], <small>GBS</small>\n|1999\u20132000\n|[[Court of Final Appeal (Hong Kong)|Non-Permanent Judge of the Court of Final Appeal]]\n|<small>QC (1985)</small>\n|-\n|3\n|[[Michael Hartmann (judge)|Michael John Hartmann]], <small>GBS</small>\n|2000\u201308\n|[[Court of Final Appeal (Hong Kong)|Non-Permanent Judge of the Court of Final Appeal]]\n|\n|-\n|4\n|[[Andrew Cheung|Andrew Cheung Kui-nung]]\n|2008\u201311\n|[[Chief Justice of the Court of Final Appeal|3rd Chief Justice of the Court of Final Appeal]]\n|\n|-\n|5\n|[[Johnson Lam Man-hon]]\n|2011\u201313\n|[[High Court of Hong Kong|Vice-President of the High Court of Hong Kong]]\n|\n|-\n|6\n|[[Thomas Au|Thomas Au Hing-cheung]]\n|2013\u201319\n|[[High Court of Hong Kong|Justice of Appeal of the High Court of Hong Kong]]\n|\n|-\n|7\n|Anderson Chow Ka-ming\n|2019\u2013\n|\n|<small>[[Senior counsel|SC]] (2004)</small>\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Hong Kong law]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong judges]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Hong Kong judges}}\nThe '''Judge in charge of the Constitutional and Administrative Law List''' of the [[Court of First Instance (Hong Kong)|Court of First Instance]] (within the [[High Court (Hong Kong)|High Court]]) of Hong Kong, is the most important Law List in that court, given the far-reaching powers of interpreting the [[Hong Kong Basic Law]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://heinonline.org/HOL/LandingPage?handle=hein.journals/judire8&div=22&id=&page=|title=Introduction to Judicial Review in Hong Kong|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> As such, the Judge in charge of this list is often considered to be the top judge of the lower court.\n\n==Description==\n\nThe list receives a material public interest in Hong Kong due to the fact that it is the first point of contact for most contentious court cases around issues that have caused public discussion or social unrest. These include cases around the [[Hong Kong Legislative Council oath-taking controversy|Legislative Council oath-taking controversy]], the [[Umbrella Movement]], and the [[2019\u201320 Hong Kong protests]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/law-and-crime/article/3033406/rare-significant-move-hong-kong-judiciary-appoints-two|title=In rare, \u2018significant\u2019 move, Hong Kong judiciary appoints two judges to hear legal challenges against anti-mask law|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In addition, given the important nature of this position, the Judge entrusted with this role is often almost guaranteed to be elevated to the higher courts in the future.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/2048895/high-court-judge-oath-taking-case-no-stranger-thorny|title=High Court judge in oath-taking case no stranger to thorny political issues|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> So far, all Judges in this role have been promoted to at least the Court of Appeal.\n\n== List of Judges==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!#\n!Name\n!Tenure\n!Promoted To (Most Senior Role) \n!Silk \n|-\n|1\n|[[Brian Keith (judge)|Sir Brian Richard Keith]]\n|1997\u201399\n|[[High Court of Hong Kong|Justice of Appeal of the High Court of Hong Kong]]\n|<small>[[Queen's Counsel|QC]] (1989)</small>\n|-\n|2\n|[[Frank Stock]]\n|1999\u20132000\n|[[Court of Final Appeal (Hong Kong